<br>
“Proof, you want,” the thing hissed at her.  “Ok, then, human.  I arrest you in the name of General V’Deers.  Please drop your weapon and prepare yourself for binding.”<br>
<br>
Melba’s axe fell from her hands, and dropped into the sand with a thud.  The Dragoon stepped forward, grabbed her shoulder, and whirled her around.  He wrapped a golden cord around her wrist.  “It’s not a rope….” Melba thought, turning her head over her shoulder to watch.   <br>
<br>
“Eyes forward, prisoner.”  The Dragoon held a gauntleted hand in front of her eyes, forcing her to turn her head to the front.  <br>
<br>
She heard the two ends of the binding clank together, and the binds tightened on her wrists.  A magical bind of some kind!  She felt a slight buzzing that, while not painful, was not comfortable.  Like the small shock one got from Wisps, if you touched them while they lived.<br>
<br>
“What about my helm?” she asked.  <br>
<br>
“We have no need of it.  The chickens will roost in it, now.”<br>
<br>
“Oh fine….” She said through gritted teeth.  “That was a gift, you know!”  He didn’t care.<br>
<br>
“You’ll take my axe with you?” she prodded.<br>
<br>
“Your weapon now belongs to the Indigo Brotherhood.  They will use it as they see fit.”<br>
<br>
Melba laughed.  “You should know, sir, that you cannot use it!  I thought they taught you about weapons at the Dragoon Academy….”<br>
<br>
“We will melt it down and use it as a weight when we drown a prisoner…..” he snarled, and pushed her between her shoulder blades.  “Walk.”<br>
<br>
They trudged on in silence.  <br>
<br>
About a mile into their hike, Melba decided it was time for some fun.  “What’s your name?”<br>
<br>
“The prisoner will remain silent.”<br>
<br>
She kept walking, but looked back at him.  “Who are you trying to impress?  There’s no one for miles! The chickens don’t care if you tell me your name.  Look!  Look…” she said pointing with her head “that cactus with the glowing yellow eyes?  He doesn’t care if you tell me your name.”  She tried to look into the Dragoons eyes, through the slit in his helmet.  Nothing but darkness.  She faced forward again.<br>
<br>
A mile later, he spoke.  “I am Dragoon Tvem of the Indigo Brotherhood, Servant of Innoruuk.”<br>
<br>
Melba smiled.  Melba – 1; Dragoon - 0.  <br>
<br>
<br>
They walked for another hour or so.  She’d never been to the Outpost in the Overthere, for obvious reasons.  She was almost pleased to be able to walk into it without having to sneak or camoflage herself, or anything.  She was a guest!  Well, of a sort.<br>
<br>
Tvem hadn’t said another word to her on their journey, and she began to feel that maybe he realized telling her his name gave Melba just a tiny bit of power over him.  Poor thing.  She wanted him to know that she meant him no harm, that she was just curious.  And still, getting that answer from him had given her a bit  of power, and she liked that.<br>
<br>
She was led to a tower just on the other side of town, and locked in a cell.  Tvem removed her bindings with, she thought, a gentler hand than when he had put them on.  Perhaps he was just tired. <br>
<br>
The truth was, he was confused.  He’d never actually spoken with a human woman that showed no fear at confronting him.  Or was she just stupid?  That could be it.  Maybe she was addled.  <br>
<br>
He was also impressed by the fact that she didn’t whine and complain on the long walk to the Outpost.  Most women whine, he knew.  Also, the binds hadn’t pained her, as they did most Followers of Light.  Or if they did, she didn’t say.   Perhaps, he mused, she could be made to turn to the ways of Innoruuk!   That would certainly be a notch on his belt, he thought.  He’d bring it up with the General at her trial.<br>
<br>
<br>
Melba had been on her knees for 10 minutes, now, and they were starting to ache.   Last night, the cell had been cold and damp, but at least there’d been some straw to sleep on, and an itchy but warmish blanket.  But here, in the Hall of Innoruuk (really just a stone shed attached to the jail, which was also a stone shed), on her knees, waiting for the judgment of the General, Melba felt discomfort.  <br>
<br>
The General had been talking at her, all this time, about how the Brotherhood would soon wage a full-scale war on the Followers of the Light (“mindless lemmings”, he called them), and how unless she repented her ways and saw fit to join the Dark ones as a slave, she was damned to eternal pain and torment.<br>
<br>
“Look,” Melba interrupted while the General was taking a breath.  “I know what you’re talking about.  I understand what you’re asking me.  There’s no need to go on for so long.  I’m not going to turn into a spy for you.  And I’m certainly not going to turn into some type of personal slave, if that’s what you’re thinking ….” She cast a glance over her shoulder at Tvem,.  “I only came here on holid….”<br>
<br>
“Silence!” the General barked.  She sighed.  “You will be persuaded.  Or you will die.”<br>
<br>
Melba grimaced.   “No, I’ve made my decision.  Kill me now.”  She bowed her head.<br>
<br>
The General was silent.<br>
<br>
“Well??” Melba asked, looking around her.  “Tvem, you were more than happy to kill me, out in the field. Why do you hesitate?”<br>
<br>
The General looked at his Dragoon.<br>
<br>
“She knows your name?”<br>
<br>
“I….Yes Sir.”<br>
<br>
The General nodded.  “Brilliant.”  <br>
<br>
Melba took a breath.  “May I speak?”<br>
<br>
The General, in a quiet voice, said “You’ve already sealed your fate, and TVems.  You can’t possibly do any more damage.  Speak, woman.”<br>
<br>
She took a deep breath.  “I don’t have an agenda.  I’m not here to playact this good/evil thing with you.  I’m here purely as a tourist.  I do my thing, you do your thing.  If your thing involves killing me, I understand!  It’s part of your whole….thing.  However, my thing involves wandering the lands, looking for some sunshine and relaxation in between bouts of furious killing, which I'm sure you can relate to.&quot;<br>
<br>
She struggled to her feet, and the General did not try to stop her.<br>
<br>
She continued.  &quot;The ONLY problem I have right now is that YOUR man, here, General, whacked the back of my head with NO provocation.  I was wearing a helmet.  There was NO WAY he could’ve known what was inside that helmet.  Am I not completely covered from head to foot?  Well, except for my helm, which T-Fal here left out on the plains to rot, thank you very much.  My question is, how did he know I was NOT a Tier D’al?  How?  Do I smell?”<br>
<br>
The General looked from Melba to his Dragoon and back.<br>
<br>
“Do you see?” Tvem asked. <br>
<br>
“She asks too many questions,” the General answered.<br>
<br>
“Yes Sir.”<br>
<br>
“I….”<br>
<br>
“Silence, prisoner”.<br>
<br>
“.....” Melba clammed up.<br>
<br>
The General walked to his desk and took out a piece of paper.  “The Law is pretty clear, when it comes to your offense, Dragoon.”<br>
<br>
“What?”  Melba looked from the General to Tvem.  “His offense??”<br>
<br>
“I told you my name,” Tvem muttered. “I broke a fundamental Dragoon Law.  I will be punished.”<br>
<br>
“Oh, that’s just silly,” Melba said to the room. <br>
<br>
“You are hereby sentenced to be bound together, in the desert, until the elements or such creatures as may find you have destroyed you utterly.”  The General sighed.  “I’m really very sorry Tvem.  But you know there are many who would take your place, here.  And telling this follower of the light your name was a grave mistake.  But it’s done.  And so are you.”<br>
<br>
Tvem looked silently ahead, still at attention.<br>
<br>
