<br>
They could see a small pool of water, just downslope from them.  From time to time, a lone scorpikis would come to drink at the pool, peering up at the two beings near the old ruins, and scurrying away again.<br>
<br>
“They’ll eventually get wise and come sniffing around us, you know” Melba said, folding her hands over her knees.  She was sitting on the dusty ground, knees drawn up in front of her, watching the sun set.   The Dragoon hadn’t spoken in the five hours they’d been alone.  The march across the desert had been brutally embarrassing for him, Melba knew.  Humiliating.  His Indigo Brotherhood surrounding him, accusations of treason clear in their silence. They would not miss him.  He had broken a law, and law-breakers must die.  No mercy, no pity.<br>
<br>
For the fourth time that afternoon, Melba said “I still don’t get it.  All you did was tell me your name.  I mean, I know it gave me a little bit of power of a sort over you…but really!  This is so archaic!”<br>
<br>
“Woman, will you not, even in impending death, cease your prattle?”<br>
<br>
“Ah hah!”   Melba smiled up at him and pointed a finger “He speaks!  I knew you would…”  She grinned.<br>
<br>
“Only to convince you to shut it,” he grumbled. <br>
<br>
Melba continued to grin.<br>
<br>
<br>
High above them, in a ruined temple on a hill, a small, dark figure peeked over a ledge and looked down at the two condemned prisoners.  The dark figure made itself very still, almost vanishing completely in the coming darkness.  The figure sighed and listened as hard as it could.  Listening, and waiting.  Looking at the sky.<br>
<br>
XXXXXX<br>
<br>
The next day dawned, slowly, sticky, hot and humid.  It was going to be even hotter than it had been for their march, obviously.  Melba wondered how long until thirst overcame her.  She hoped, rather, for a Rhino goring.  At least that would be quick.  Or a puma!  Ahh, for just one hungry puma.  Or poison!  Perhaps those Scorpikis carried a lethal poison.  Perhaps today they wouldn’t be so frightened of them.<br>
<br>
“Take your armor off, TVem.”<br>
<br>
“What??” the Dragoon asked, startled out of his meditations.  Innoruuk, it seemed, had left him.  He couldn’t call up thoughts of revenge he knew he should be planning against this Woman.  He couldn’t muster up the hatred for her that would make his death more meaningful.  All he could think of was how miserably hot it was, and how thirsty he was, and how much he wished he was back home in Neriak, and not in this stinking dry, awful place, tied to this stinking, awful human.<br>
<br>
“If you take off your armor, you won’t scare the Scorps away. That’s why they’re not coming over here:  they know who you are.  You big scary Dragoon, you,” she buffeted him on the shoulder, grinning.  Man, he was cranky.  “Man, you’re cranky.  Anyway, just take it off, and let them see that you’re really all soft and squishy inside, and then they’ll come over here, poison us, and it’ll all be over and done with and we can go reside forever with our respective Gods.  Ok??”  <br>
<br>
Melba stood and began peeling off her Ry’Gorr.  <br>
<br>
“Ah!  Oh!” she cried out, folding the armor as best she could into neat piles and dropping it unceremoniously on the dusty ground.  “That feels SO much better, anyway!”  The mail had left rings impressed in her skin, so she looked as though she had the Pox.  “Dang,” she rubbed her arms.  “That stuff chafes.  I do miss plain leather, let me tell you!”<br>
<br>
She was now wearing a pair of calf-length black rough woven leggings, a white undershirt, and a small bright blue corset, which barely concealed her…womanly charms.  TVem watched her fold her armor, then looked away, embarrassed at having been looking at her at all.  <br>
<br>
“I’ve naught on under this…” he said.<br>
<br>
“You….what?  No!”  she laughed, crossing her arms over her chest.  She knew he had looked.  She felt bad making him uncomfortable.  Aw, no she didn’t.  She uncrossed her arms.  “No, really??  That’s unfortunate.  I’m sorry.”  She did indeed feel bad for him, as taking off her armor had helped cool her immeasurably.  <br>
<br>
And he almost, almost could feel her pity.  He wasn’t sure what to make of it.  No one had ever pitied him before.<br>
<br>
But he took his helmet off, at any rate.   Melba wasn’t quite ready for it.  She was kicking her dusty boots closer to the column, and noticed movement out of the corner of her eye.  Looking up, she saw him just as the helmet let go of his hair. <br>
<br>
His thick white hair hung down in stringy ropes to his shoulders.  His skin was as dark blue as a Teir’Dal’s skin could be.  He had white eyes.  He was beautiful.   <br>
<br>
His eyes held such pain, though.  And something else.  Anger?  Resentment?  No.  No, it was confusion, Melba thought.<br>
<br>
“Well, look at you!” Melba faced him and put her hands on her hips.  “Aren’t you the handsome devil.  Why on earth are you hiding yourself from all those lovely young Tier’Dal girls??  You’re quite the catch!”<br>
<br>
“Please!  Please stop with the…..”  he stopped.  It occurred to him that he was going to die here, with this woman.  And it also occurred to him that she was never going to cease her relentless efforts to lighten his mood.  So he would do something he had never in his life done.  For his life was ending, now, and why shouldn’t he try a new approach, for variety’s sake.  He would give in.<br>
<br>
He looked out at the distant horizon, watching dark grey storm clouds gathering.  A light wind whipped his hair into his eyes.<br>
<br>
“I was married, once,” he said, setting down his helmet.  He began to unclasp his Breastplate.<br>
<br>
“You were??”<br>
<br>
“She died in battle.  Killed by a High Elf Paladin.  Who died immediately after on the end of my sword.”<br>
<br>
Melba was silent.  “I’m so sorry” she said, after a bit.<br>
<br>
He had finished unclasping the breastplate, and removed it.  The sleeves followed.  Underneath, there was a tunic of black woven grass, horribly rusted and worn.  <br>
<br>
“You said you had nothing on under there,” Melba said quietly.<br>
<br>
“I lied.  I didn’t want to take it off, but you were right.  It’s much cooler this way.”  He took the metal leggings off, to show thin brown, worn, and rusted leather leggings.  He finished removing all the metal…stooped and grabbed it up in his arms, and hurled it as hard as he could at the force field surrounding them.  It slowed momentarily, and then popped through to the other side.<br>
<br>
“Hm,” he grunted, eyes blinking with sweat.<br>
<br>
“That was interesting,” Melba agreed.<br>
<br>
“Perhaps it’s not as strong as we think it is,” TVem remarked.<br>
<br>
“Wait!  Wait!  Oh yes it is!” said a voice, behind them, and up the hill.  They whirled.<br>
<br>
“Ha ha!  Look at the two of you!  Naked to the world!  You would think you were already dead, a human and a Teir’Dal, unclothed and together.”<br>
<br>
The small creature descended a little-used path in the hillside.  As it got closer, they saw it was also a Dark Elf.  A girl.  A very, very young girl.  Wearing naught but the things her guild would have given her, to set out in life as, say, a necromancer.<br>
<br>
The two prisoners gaped at her.<br>
<br>
“Pushing things through the wall only makes it stronger.  Now my work will be that much more difficult,” she scolded. <br>
<br>
The small dark elf sat down on the ground and began to sift sand through her fingers.  She looked up at them.  “I only need a little more, from near the cell wall, so that it’s been touched by the magics,” she babbled at them.<br>
<br>
She filtered out the rougher sand, until nothing was left in her hand but a black metallic dust.  She held it as close to her eyes as she could, then she sniffed at it and nodded.  She untied a small bag from her waist and poured the black sand in.  She set the bag on the ground, and began to sway and hum in front of it.  Little sparks of light came off her fingers from time to time, arching over the bag, fluttering up into the sky.  After about ten minutes, the swaying stopped. She stood up, and put the bag on the ground at the apex of the plain air, and the cell wall.<br>
<br>
“Now we wait for the Gods,” she said in a whisper, eyes wide, staring at Melba.<br>
<br>
She stepped back and began to jump up and down in place, humming slightly, occasionally gesturing at the clouds.<br>
<br>
The storm grew closer.<br>
<br>
Melba and TVem stood, transfixed by the girls antics.  Could she really be helping them in some way?  Or was she just another desert lunatic?<br>
<br>
Lightning flashed in the sky above them, the thunder almost simultaneous.  “No rain!”  the girl shouted at the sky “No rain yet!  You hear me, Gods, you hear me!”  It wasn’t a question.<br>
<br>
The air was warm and the sky was almost black, for all it was mid day.  Suddenly, silence.  The wind stopped, and there was a CRASH and a bright light.  The girl was pointing at the bag, or where the bag had been.  It was just a small bit of black rock, now, and some blue smoke.  <br>
<br>
“RUN!  Run to me!” she shouted at them.  Melba didn’t hesitate, and dashed straight towards the girl.  After a small moment, TVem ran through. <br>
<br>
They were free.<br>
