<br>
Melba grabbed TVems hand and ran.  The girl dashed after them.  They didn’t stop, didn’t speak, until the reached the valley beyond the Frontier Mountain border.  Collapsing against a tree, Melba found the breath to ask “Who are you?”<br>
<br>
The girl leapt to her feet and swept into a bow.  “I am Parriah, Lady Melba, at your service.”<br>
<br>
Melba smiled. “You know me??”<br>
<br>
“Well, sort of, ma’am.  I am your niece.”<br>
<br>
Melba boggled.<br>
<br>
“Niece??”<br>
<br>
“When was the last time you saw your brother, milady?”<br>
<br>
“……” Melba thought.  At least 15 years.<br>
<br>
“But….”<br>
<br>
“There has been no wedding, of course.  An Erudite and a Teir’Dal?  Nooo….” Parriah laughed. “My mother found the ways of Innoruuk a bit too… constraining.  She craved learning…she LOVED to read!  So, on a clandestine visit to the Freeport library, she met my father…your own brother!  They fell in love, and here I am.  They live together, now, in Erudin.  But for many, many years, mother and I had to live in Neriak.  Her parents (grammy and grampy) weren’t too keen on the match.  Only lately did they allow her to leave and visit him…” she looked down at the ground.  “Well, they died, actually,” she said quietly.  <br>
<br>
She took a breath and shrugged.  “So, we snuck away and went to live with dad.  And it’s been super!!  I LOVE it there!”  she smiled and threw some grass into the air.  “It’s not all dark and depressing.  It’s a bit quiet, but there’s some nightlife, in the Warrens, where all the young kids hang out.”<br>
<br>
“But then Uncle Damdor came and said you were missing, so we did some magics, and found you were here.  I came and tracked you, and here we are.  Good thing I learned some of grampys more necrotic spells.  Blowing things up, sneaking around.  You should’ve seen me sneaking around Freeport to get to the silly wooden barge that goes to the Outpost!  I’m only 15, you know.” She smiled.<br>
<br>
“A relative eh?” asked TVem.  “She certainly has your mouth!” he teased Melba.<br>
<br>
Melba pointed at him and boggled.  “You smiled!!!!”<br>
<br>
He threw a dirt clod at her, missing her by a mile.<br>
<br>
XXXXXXXXXXXXXXX<br>
<br>
They didn’t sit around the Frontier Mountains for too long.  The made camp by the stream, near the Firiona Vie border.  They bought some food and water from a passing party of adventurers, lit a fire, and made their plans.<br>
<br>
Parriah had taken the boat from the Oasis to the Overthere Outpost, but had managed to send a dark elf-friendly courier on ahead to Firiona with money enough to buy new clothes and traveling provisions.  She hadn’t counted on bringing a Dragoon into Firiona, as well, so they had to camp at the Lake for a few days while she searched out ways of disguising not one but TWO Teir’Dal, on the boat trip to Butcher Block.  Where they would catch a boat to Freeport.  And from there….oh, the thought of that overland trip to Qeynos was too much for Melba.<br>
<br>
“The guards there don’t like me in Freeport,” Melba hesitated.  <br>
<br>
“Me either,” TVem and Parriah both chimed in.<br>
<br>
“Let’s get translocated, instead,” Melba suggested.<br>
<br>
“Oooh, Aunty Melba, that’s a LOT of money….Uncle Damdor gave me some, but I don’t think enough to Translocate three people!!” she looked sadly at TVem, who bonked her gently on the head.<br>
<br>
“I have plenty enough money,” Melba said.  “I’ll head into town tomorrow and get it.  You two look for someone who can push us out of here.  Deal?  I don’t want to take a chance that either of you will drop your disguise while we’re in Firiona.  It’s far too dangerous.”<br>
<br>
Parriah looked up at TVem and down at the ground.  “Ok, Aunty Melba”.<br>
<br>
Melba looked stricken.  “Oh, hon! I’m sorry!  You must’ve wanted to see Firiona so much!  I understand!  But you’ve come so far!  I can’t have you getting killed just to save ME!  Your daddy would kill me!!”  She lifted Parriah’s chin and smiled at her.  “One day, when you’re older, I Promise I’ll bring you back here.  We’ll take all the boats…from Odus to Qeynos…then we’ll run as fast as we can to Freeport…then the boat to Butcherblock, and then on the Maiden’s Voyage to Firiona!  Ok?”<br>
<br>
“The Maiden’s Voyage?  Promise?”<br>
<br>
“I promise!” Melba answered.  “Once I have Superior Camo Against Everything That Might Kill A Young Teir’Dal Niece, that is” she thought to herself.<br>
<br>
<br>
XXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXX<br>
<br>
Melba’s trip to Firiona was uneventful.   She got the money, and foraged a Rose of Firiona for Parriah, as a souvenir.   She’d have to make good on her promise, one day, she knew.<br>
 <br>
Crossing the stream back into the Lake area, Melba thought “How many days has it been since I was last here?  It seems months!  Although it was only just a week or two.”  Setting her track on her niece, she was surprised to pick up a subliminal sort of distress call from Parriah.<br>
<br>
“Come, Aunty Melba!  Come quickly!”  Melba ran for them.<br>
<br>
Crossing the hill with no buffs on and only an old sword (thankfully, she’d left some of her older weapons in the bank at Firiona), she came upon a scene that brought her immediately back to that last day, when the Dragoons had set the force field around them.  V’Lask had been the one to remove TVem’s badge from his breastplate; the one who used TVem’s own knife to slice the ‘X’ through TVem’s Indigo Brotherhood tattoo.  It was still bleeding slightly, despite Melba’s (at first clandestine) heals.<br>
<br>
V’Lask stood, sword to the throat of the little girl, facing TVem.  He and the girl were just in the stream, close to the shore.  Tvem was on the shore, and his hands were halfway up, in a placating position.  She knew that this standoff would not end easily.  Both men considered Black to each other, as it were.  The Teir’Dal testosterone was flying.<br>
<br>
She sheathed her blade and walked slowly towards the scene unfolding by the gently running stream.<br>
<br>
“Stay back, Human,” V’Lask hissed.  “I can smell your stink from here.”<br>
<br>
“Nice manners, Dragoon,” she grimaced.  “You know, I used to have a sort of sick respect for your kind,” she sauntered a bit closer to the water.  “But now I see you for the oppressive, bigoted tools of Innoruuk that you really are.”  She spat in derision.  She was pretty pleased with that, and filed it away to try it again on someone it might actually impress.<br>
        <br>
“Let my niece go, and you can have your Brother back,” Melba suggested.<br>
<br>
Tvem didn’t even look her way.  She knew he knew she was bluffing.<br>
<br>
“Your niece?” the Dragoon hissed.  “How can this dark one be related to a quivering piece of useless flesh like you?”<br>
<br>
“You’re just pleasant as pie, aren’t you?  Gods…” Melba unsheathed her sword and stuck the tip of it into the dirt.<br>
<br>
“It is not my duty to be pleasant to scum,” he responded.<br>
<br>
“Look, just let her go…..”<br>
<br>
Tvem hadn’t been placating the other Dragoon with his hand gestures.  He’d been measuring.  Now, he lunged.  With one fist he punched V’Lask in the throat, knocking him into the stream, and with the other he propelled Parriah over to Melba.   His hand remained open, in the air, facing Melba.  She tossed him her sword, and in one fluid movement, Tvem was standing on V’Lasks chest, his foot just over his heart, Melba’s sword tip at his throat.<br>
<br>
“It’s important to not be a ghost, brother.  I have been a ghost here for so long,” TVem spat in the water, breathing hard.  “I want my name back.  I want to find peace.  Maybe find a wife. No one will ever replace K’vrin, but maybe I can have a different life with someone new.  Someone who is through with vengeance and pointless slaughter.  Just let us be on our way, Brother, and I won’t remove your head.”<br>
<br>
Dragoon V’Lask looked at his ex-brother, his ex-friend.  His friend.  He was breathing hard, yet was very still.  The water from the stream spilled into his mouth, and he spat it back out. <br>
<br>
“I would have killed you, Brother.  As you should kill me, now.”<br>
<br>
“I will not.”<br>
<br>
“Then….we are at a stalemate.”<br>
<br>
“Yes.”<br>
<br>
The two Dragoons stared into each other’s eyes for a good minute.  Suddenly, a sturgeon began to nip at V’Lask’s foot.  Tvem looked down and laughed in surprise.  V’Lask looked horrified, but Tvem removed his foot from his chest, and gave him his hand.  “Let me save you from the fish, Brother” Tvem said.  V’Lask hesitated a moment, but took the hand.  They sloshed up onto the shore.<br>
<br>
The two Dragoons regarded each other intently, for a moment.  Melba was afraid V’Lask would lash out.  But he spoke.<br>
<br>
“Go, then.  You are dead to the Indigo Brotherhood.  I have killed you.   You are a ghost to us.”  He turned his back and headed in the direction of the Frontier Mountains border.  Halfway up the hill he paused, briefly, but did not turn.  “Go be alive, somewhere else, Tvem.  For all of us.”  He continued up the hill, and disappeared.<br>
